<task id="AIPU2-060" project="Spaarke AI Platform Unification R2">
  <metadata>
    <title>Full ISprkAgent Implementation + DirectOpenAiAgent</title>
    <phase>3</phase>
    <tags>bff-api, ai, architecture</tags>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>4 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>AIPU2-008, AIPU2-015</dependencies>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>
  <prompt>
    Define the ISprkAgent interface and implement DirectOpenAiAgent so that all R2 chat flows route
    through a single, well-typed agent abstraction. R1 used ad-hoc service calls scattered across
    ChatEndpoints; R2 requires every chat turn to go through ISprkAgent so that the factory, router,
    and safety pipeline all have a stable seam to attach to. DirectOpenAiAgent wraps the Azure OpenAI
    Responses SDK call (established in AIPU2-008) and exposes the streaming result as an
    IAsyncEnumerable of SseEvent. AIPU2-015 (CapabilityRouter) provides the tool list injected per
    turn; this task binds the two together at the interface level.
  </prompt>
  <role>Senior .NET developer with Azure OpenAI SDK and streaming API experience.</role>
  <goal>
    All R2 chat flows use DirectOpenAiAgent via the ISprkAgent interface. The interface compiles,
    DirectOpenAiAgent passes unit tests for streaming output, and no chat endpoint calls the Azure
    OpenAI SDK directly without going through ISprkAgent.
  </goal>
  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Chat/SprkChatAgentFactory.cs</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-013-ai-architecture.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>
  <steps>
    <step>Read SprkChatAgentFactory.cs and ADR-013 to understand the current agent creation pattern and constraints.</step>
    <step>Define ISprkAgent interface in Services/Ai/Chat/ISprkAgent.cs with methods: ExecuteTurnAsync(ChatTurnRequest, IReadOnlyList&lt;AiTool&gt;, CancellationToken) returning IAsyncEnumerable&lt;SseEvent&gt;, and GetAgentMetadata() returning AgentMetadata record.</step>
    <step>Create DirectOpenAiAgent.cs implementing ISprkAgent, wrapping the Azure OpenAI Responses SDK streaming call established in AIPU2-008.</step>
    <step>Ensure DirectOpenAiAgent accepts injected IReadOnlyList&lt;AiTool&gt; per turn (not a static list) so AIPU2-061 can later drive tool selection via CapabilityRouter.</step>
    <step>Register ISprkAgent and DirectOpenAiAgent in DI (Program.cs or the AI service registration extension).</step>
    <step>Write unit tests covering: streaming tokens emitted in order, cancellation token respected, empty tool list handled gracefully.</step>
    <step>Verify no ChatEndpoints code calls the Azure OpenAI SDK client directly — all calls must go through ISprkAgent.</step>
  </steps>
  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>ISprkAgent interface exists in Services/Ai/Chat/ and compiles cleanly.</criterion>
    <criterion>DirectOpenAiAgent implements ISprkAgent and is registered in DI.</criterion>
    <criterion>Unit tests for DirectOpenAiAgent pass (streaming, cancellation, empty tools).</criterion>
    <criterion>No direct Azure OpenAI SDK calls remain in ChatEndpoints — all routed via ISprkAgent.</criterion>
    <criterion>ADR-013 constraints are not violated (AI Tool Framework; extend BFF, not separate service).</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
